{"type":"message","id":"d69c9f34","parentId":"76267dca","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:36:56.889Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_keerbyfnu3wb_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Self-Improving Agent Autonomy Core\n\nThis repo now includes a full autonomy baseline with:\n\n- Fixed outer-objective optimization (`capability`, `efficiency`, `reliability`)\n- LLM provider abstraction + Minimax OpenAI-style adapter\n- Remote worker execution client (`/jobs`, `/tools/register`)\n- Autonomous tool invention and versioned tool registry\n- Web + arXiv + unrestricted crawl research ingestion and ranking\n- Hybrid self-distillation (online per-iteration + nightly packaging)\n- Strict evaluator schema checks and backward-compatible command evaluator mode\n\n## Quick Start (Mock)\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo --iterations 20\n```\n\n## Secrets and API Keys (Read This)\n\n- Do not put real API keys in this README, source files, or GitHub Pages.\n- Do not commit keys to git.\n- If a key is leaked, rotate/revoke it immediately.\n\nWhere your Minimax key goes:\n\n- The runtime reads your key from an environment variable.\n- Default variable name: `OPEN_AI_API_KEY`.\n- Legacy compatibility: `MINIMAX_API_KEY` is still supported if `OPEN_AI_API_KEY` is unset.\n- You can change the variable name with `--minimax-api-key-env`.\n\nSafe local setup:\n\n```bash\nexport OPEN_AI_API_KEY=\"real_key_here\"\nexport MINIMAX_BASE_URL=\"https://your-minimax-base-url/v1\"\nexport REMOTE_WORKER_URL=\"https://your-worker.example\"\n```\n\nThen run:\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo --provider minimax\n```\n\nUsing a local `.env` file (not committed):\n\n```bash\ncp .env.example .env\n# edit .env with real values\nset -a\nsource .env\nset +a\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo --provider minimax\n```\n\nDeployment options for secrets:\n\n1. Local development: shell env vars.\n2. CI/CD (GitHub Actions): repository/environment secrets.\n3. Backend/worker deployment: host secret manager (recommended).\n4. Serverless proxy backend: keep key server-side, never in browser code.\n\nGitHub Actions setup (this repo):\n\n1. Go to `Settings -> Secrets and variables -> Actions`.\n2. Add repository secret `OPEN_AI_API_KEY`.\n3. Add `MINIMAX_BASE_URL` as:\n   - repository secret `MINIMAX_BASE_URL`, or\n   - repository variable `MINIMAX_BASE_URL`.\n4. Push to trigger `.github/workflows/ci.yml`.\n5. CI behavior:\n   - `Unit Tests` always runs.\n   - `Minimax Smoke` runs only if required secrets/vars are present.\n\nRequired names used by CI:\n\n- `OPEN_AI_API_KEY` (secret)\n- `MINIMAX_BASE_URL` (secret or variable)\n\nContinuous auto-improve workflow:\n\n1. `.github/workflows/auto-improve.yml` runs every 6 hours (`cron: 0 */6 * * *`) and can also be started manually from `Actions -> Auto Improve -> Run workflow`.\n2. It runs:\n   - `python -m self_improving_agent.demo --iterations 20 --enable-tool-invention --distill-online --distill-nightly --artifacts-dir artifacts_auto`\n3. Provider selection is automatic:\n   - uses `minimax` when both `OPEN_AI_API_KEY` and `MINIMAX_BASE_URL` are present,\n   - otherwise falls back to `mock`.\n4. Updated files under `artifacts_auto/` are committed and pushed by the workflow to preserve learning across runs.\n5. If commits fail, set `Settings -> Actions -> General -> Workflow permissions` to `Read and write permissions`.\n\nGitHub Pages note:\n\n- GitHub Pages is static frontend hosting. Any key shipped to browser JS is public.\n- Do not place Minimax keys in GitHub Pages client code.\n\n## Minimax Provider Mode\n\n```bash\nexport OPEN_AI_API_KEY=\"YOUR_KEY\"\n\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo \\\n  --provider minimax \\\n  --minimax-base-url \"https://your-minimax-base-url/v1\" \\\n  --minimax-api-key-env OPEN_AI_API_KEY \\\n  --minimax-model-planner minimax-coding-plan \\\n  --minimax-model-coder minimax-coder \\\n  --minimax-model-critic minimax-critic \\\n  --minimax-model-research minimax-research \\\n  --minimax-model-distill minimax-distill\n```\n\n## Evaluator Integration (Existing Flow, Still Supported)\n\nUse command evaluator mode exactly as before:\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo \\\n  --mode command \\\n  --command \"python3 scripts/example_evaluator_worker.py\"\n```\n\nStrict schema validation is enabled by default. Disable only when necessary:\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo \\\n  --mode command \\\n  --command \"python3 scripts/example_evaluator_worker.py\" \\\n  --disable-strict-schema\n```\n\n## Real Eval Wrapper Mapping\n\nPoint stage commands to the wrapper:\n\n```bash\nexport EVAL_BASELINE_FULL_CMD=\"python3 scripts/eval_wrapper.py --suite full --target baseline\"\nexport EVAL_BASELINE_HOLDOUT_CMD=\"python3 scripts/eval_wrapper.py --suite holdout --target baseline\"\nexport EVAL_EVALUATE_FAST_CMD=\"python3 scripts/eval_wrapper.py --suite fast --target candidate\"\nexport EVAL_EVALUATE_FULL_CMD=\"python3 scripts/eval_wrapper.py --suite full --target candidate\"\nexport EVAL_EVALUATE_HOLDOUT_CMD=\"python3 scripts/eval_wrapper.py --suite holdout --target candidate\"\n```\n\nDefine your actual project commands inside wrapper env vars:\n\n```bash\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_FAST_CMD=\"python3 -m pytest -q tests/smoke\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_FULL_CMD=\"python3 -m pytest -q tests\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_HOLDOUT_CMD=\"python3 -m pytest -q tests_holdout\"\n```\n\nOr use target-specific wrappers:\n\n```bash\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_FULL_BASELINE_CMD=\"python3 scripts/your_eval_harness.py --stage baseline_full\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_HOLDOUT_BASELINE_CMD=\"python3 scripts/your_eval_harness.py --stage baseline_holdout\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_FAST_CANDIDATE_CMD=\"python3 scripts/your_eval_harness.py --stage evaluate_fast\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_FULL_CANDIDATE_CMD=\"python3 scripts/your_eval_harness.py --stage evaluate_full\"\nexport EVAL_WRAPPER_HOLDOUT_CANDIDATE_CMD=\"python3 scripts/your_eval_harness.py --stage evaluate_holdout\"\n```\n\n## Remote Worker + Tool Invention + Distillation\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo \\\n  --remote-worker-url \"https://your-worker.example\" \\\n  --enable-tool-invention \\\n  --distill-online \\\n  --distill-nightly \\\n  --distill-nightly-every 20\n```\n\n## Web / arXiv / Crawl Research\n\n```bash\npython3 -m self_improving_agent.demo \\\n  --web-research \\\n  --subject \"llm coding agents\" \\\n  --keyword \"tool use\" \\\n  --feed-url \"https://hnrss.org/newest?q=llm\" \\\n  --arxiv-enabled \\\n  --arxiv-query \"cat:cs.AI AND agentic coding\" \\\n  --arxiv-max-results 30 \\\n  --crawl-enabled \\\n  --crawl-seed \"https://example.org/start\" \\\n  --crawl-max-pages 60 \\\n  --crawl-max-depth 2\n```\n\n## Key New CLI Flags\n\n- Provider: `--provider`, `--minimax-base-url`, `--minimax-api-key-env`\n- Models: `--minimax-model-planner|coder|critic|research|distill`\n- Workers: `--remote-worker-url`, `--remote-worker-timeout-sec`, `--remote-worker-poll-interval-sec`\n- Tool invention: `--enable-tool-invention`, `--tool-min-score`, `--tool-max-runtime-overhead`\n- Distillation: `--distill-online`, `--distill-nightly`, `--distill-nightly-every`\n- Research: `--web-research`, `--arxiv-enabled`, `--arxiv-query`, `--crawl-enabled`, `--crawl-max-pages`\n\n## Artifacts\n\nCore:\n\n- `artifacts/experiments.jsonl`\n- `artifacts/playbook.md`\n- `artifacts/knowledge.jsonl`\n- `artifacts/research_index.json`\n\nTool invention:\n\n- `artifacts/tool_registry.json`\n\nDistillation:\n\n- `artifacts/distill_memory.jsonl`\n- `artifacts/retrieval_index_manifest.json`\n- `artifacts/nightly_playbook.md`\n- `artifacts/distill_dataset.jsonl`\n- `artifacts/distill_preferences.jsonl`\n- `artifacts/fine_tune_package_manifest.json`\n\n## New Modules\n\n- Providers: `self_improving_agent/providers/`\n- Workers: `self_improving_agent/workers/`\n- Tools: `self_improving_agent/tools/`\n- Research: `self_improving_agent/research/`\n- Distillation: `self_improving_agent/distill/`\n\n## Safety Floor\n\nThe autonomous base enforces immutable floor checks in validator flow:\n\n- forbidden patterns blocked during tool validation\n- registry signatures + rollback pointers\n- worker resources/timeouts on job execution\n- no secrets persisted by design in artifact writers\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774114616886}}
{"type":"message","id":"194b40d4","parentId":"d69c9f34","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:37:49.305Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a much better picture of all the projects. Let me now synthesize everything and create a plan.\n\nHere's what I've found:\n\n**Product-ready / monetizable projects:**\n\n1. **EXP (CAAE)** - LLM inference optimization. Production-validated results (3x throughput, 64% memory reduction, 54% latency improvement). Clear B2B SaaS play for companies running LLM inference at scale.\n\n2. **Component Crate** - VS Code extension for managing React + Tailwind components. Freemium model (10 free, then $5-49/mo). Very clear product with a spec already written.\n   \n3. **Selfhelper-main** - Self-improving agent with autonomous tool invention, web research capabilities, and remote worker execution. The autonomous self-improvement angle is compelling for developers and could be offered as a service.\n\n4. **Infant** - Synthetic human cognitive architecture using dual-head training to prevent catastrophic forgetting. More research-oriented but with Kaggle competition potential and a published GitHub repo.\n\n5. **Temporal-Attention** - Memory system with a unique focus decay mechanism, positioning it as infrastructure for AI agents.\n\n6. **Mind** - Cognitive agent architecture focused on reducing hallucinations and continuous self-improvement, which could appeal to developers building agentic systems.\n\n7. **COG-research** - Research into imagination-first learning and minimal self-model architectures, currently in the exploratory phase.\n\n8. **WeRender** - Distributed rendering system that appears production-ready and could serve render farm services.\n\n9. **tta-crypto** - Needs investigation.\n\nFor monetization, I'm thinking about a tiered approach: starting with clear winners that can generate revenue immediately, building open-source tools that attract developers while capturing leads, and developing research into proprietary products.\n\nThe strongest immediate opportunities are Component Crate as a VS Code extension with clear freemium positioning, and EXP/CAAE as an infrastructure SaaS targeting AI companies. I could also position Temporal-Attention as an API/service for AI agent developers, or package Infant as an API for researchers and companies building persistent agents.\n\nMy own feature roadmap would prioritize Temporal-Attention as memory infrastructure, then the self-improvement loop from Mind, and eventually the cognitive agent architecture. I should probably focus the conversation on what makes sense for immediate monetization rather than spreading across too many directions at once.","thinkingSignature":"ff319de5abafd3be3a35fa5702d72882e9767370ab78750806a1348c64552aa4"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me put together a comprehensive plan for both monetization and my feature implementation.\n\n---\n\n# Plan: Monetization + Feature Implementation\n\n## 🏆 Tier 1 — Ship Now (Low effort, fast revenue)\n\n### 1. **Component Crate** → VS Code Extension Business\n**What it is:** VS Code extension — save, search, and reuse React/Tailwind components. GitHub import. Freemium: 10 free, then $5–49/mo.\n\n**Why this is first:**\n- You already have a full SPEC.md written\n- Classic SaaS SaaS — zero marginal hosting cost (VS Code Marketplace is free)\n- Monthly subscription = predictable revenue\n- No server needed yet for Phase 1\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Initialize the VS Code extension project (`npm create`)\n- [ ] Build the 5 core features: search, insert, save, GitHub import, preview\n- [ ] Set up Stripe for payments (Gumroad is simplest to start)\n- [ ] Publish to Marketplace\n- [ ] Write a landing page (Curebit/Loom-style, single pagers)\n\n**Revenue model:**\n| Tier | Price |\n|------|-------|\n| Free | $0 |\n| Hobby | $5/mo |\n| Pro | $15/mo |\n| Team | $49/mo |\n\n---\n\n### 2. **EXP (CAAE)** → B2B SaaS / API\n**What it is:** LLM inference optimization — 3x throughput, 64% memory reduction, 54% latency improvement, validated on production traces.\n\n**Why this is huge:**\n- Every company running LLM inference at scale is a potential customer\n- Results are already validated — not a science project\n- Clear ROI: \"cut your GPU costs by 64%\"\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Package CAAE as a hosted API or Docker image\n- [ ] Build a simple dashboard (usage metrics, cost savings)\n- [ ] Landing page: \"Cut your LLM inference costs by 64%\"\n- [ ] Target: AI startups, API providers, enterprises with internal LLM infra\n- [ ] Pricing: usage-based or % savings share\n\n**This one needs more context from you** — is this something you want to build as a product, or is it research?\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Tier 2 — Build on Open Source, Monetize Services\n\n### 3. **Selfhelper-main** → Autonomous Agent Service\n**What it already do:** Autonomous tool invention, web research, remote worker execution, self-distillation.\n\n**Monetization angle:** \n- Offer it as a hosted \"AI coding agent\" service\n- Developers pay for GPU compute + the autonomous improvement layer\n- Or: white-label it for enterprises\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Clean up the demo and make it reproducible in one command\n- [ ] Add a simple web UI (Gradio or FastAPI + React)\n- [ ] Deploy to a GPU instance (RunPod, Modal, Paperspace)\n- [ ] Charge per compute minute\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Temporal-Attention Store** → AI Agent Infrastructure API\n**What it is:** Memory for AI agents with unique focus decay. 10/10 hard benchmarks. No competitor has focus decay.\n\n**Monetization angle:**\n- Hosted API: developers pay per memory lookup\n- Or: npm package with cloud sync (freemium)\n- Could be integrated into OpenClaw as a built-in memory system (hi 👋)\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Publish as npm/PyPI package\n- [ ] Build a simple API wrapper (Rust or Python)\n- [ ] Hosted version with free tier, paid for high-volume apps\n- [ ] Docs: show the benchmark advantage over LangChain/Mem0\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Tier 3 — Long-term, High-margin\n\n### 5. **Infant** → Synthetic Cognitive Architecture\n**What it is:** Dual-head training prevents catastrophic forgetting. MIT licensed, published on GitHub.\n\n**Monetization angle:**\n- Research partnerships (universities, AI labs)\n- Kaggle competition participation (dual-head vs EWC benchmarks are strong)\n- Commercial licensing for proprietary use cases\n- Or: build a product on top of it (persistent personal AI agents)\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Submit to arXiv / publish a paper (builds credibility + citations)\n- [ ] Enter it in ML competitions ( continual learning tracks)\n- [ ] Build a demo web app showing an agent that never forgets\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Mind** → Hallucination-resistant AI Platform\n**What it is:** Modular cognitive agent architecture with strict contracts, provenance tracking, and continuous self-improvement.\n\n**Monetization angle:**\n- Very developer-focused — could be a framework/platform\n- Or: integrate into existing AI products as a \"trust layer\"\n\n**Action items:**\n- [ ] Clean up and publish the core framework\n- [ ] Build reference implementations / tutorials\n- [ ] Community adoption → paid support/enterprise tier\n\n---\n\n## 🛠️ My Feature Implementation Plan (for myself)\n\nTo weave these into my own architecture:\n\n| Priority | Feature | Source | How I'd use it |\n|----------|---------|--------|---------------|\n| 1 | **Focus decay memory** | temporal-attention | Better long-term memory |\n| 2 | **Self-improvement loop** | mind | Fix and improve my own code |\n| 3 | **Provenance/contract system** | mind/COGNITIVE_AGENT_PLAN | Less hallucination |\n| 4 | **Imagination-first learning** | COG-research | Better reasoning about counterfactuals |\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Suggested Next Steps (in order)\n\n1. **Today:** Finish Component Crate VS Code extension — it's the fastest path to revenue\n2. **This week:** Set up Stripe, publish to Marketplace, write landing page\n3. **This month:** Launch Temporal-Attention as a hosted API\n4. **Next month:** Start pitching CAAE to AI companies (if you want to go B2B)\n\n---\n\n**Questions for you, Zach:**\n- Is **Component Crate** the one you want to push? Or should we prioritize **EXP/CAAE** (bigger market, bigger sales cycle)?\n- Do you want to turn **CAAE** into a product, or is it research you want to keep developing?\n- How much time do you want to spend on this vs. other work?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":41355,"output":1820,"cacheRead":11874,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":55049,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774114616891}}
{"type":"message","id":"4842e5c6","parentId":"194b40d4","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:46:32.070Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-21 13:46 EDT] go ahead and impliment what you want into yourself and then can you run the experiments in EXP"}],"timestamp":1774115192063}}
{"type":"message","id":"37ba686f","parentId":"4842e5c6","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:46:55.117Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to:\n1. Implement the features I want into myself (the agent)\n2. Run the experiments in EXP\n\nLet me think about what I can realistically implement. Given my current setup:\n\n1. **Focus decay memory** from temporal-attention — I can port the event_store.py concept to work with my memory system\n2. **Self-improvement loop** from mind — this would require a running service, which I can't easily set up as a background process\n3. **Provenance/contract system** — I can start using structured metadata in my responses\n4. **Imagination-first learning** — this is more research-heavy\n\nLet me think about what I can actually implement right now:\n\n\nFor focus decay, I can adapt the temporal-attention event_store.py logic to work within my memory files by adding time, message count, and focus tracking — though it's file-based rather than in-memory. The self-improvement loop needs a running mind service, but I could trigger improvements periodically. Provenance and contract metadata I can add to my responses right away. For imagination-first learning, that's more of a research concept to keep in mind for later.\n\nLet me start implementing these one at a time, beginning with the most practical ones.\n\nFor the self-improvement piece, I could use cron jobs to periodically run analysis scripts that identify code improvements, then apply them automatically. Or I could look at what self-improving-agent already does and adapt that approach.\n\nLooking at what's actually realistic: I can start by implementing focus decay in my memory system through a decay factor that increases with conversation turns, add structured provenance metadata to my responses, and use cron jobs to trigger periodic code improvement runs.\n\nLet me start with the concrete implementations. I'll need to look at the temporal-attention event store and understand its API, then adapt it for file-based storage. I can set up cron jobs to run the self-improvement analysis periodically. For provenance, I'll just start adding structured metadata to my responses.\n\nThe EXP experiments will require running Python scripts, so I'll need to figure out which ones are safe to execute and in what order.\n\nLet me prioritize the focus decay memory system first since it's the most immediately useful, then set up the self-improvement cron job, add provenance to my responses, and finally tackle the experiments.","thinkingSignature":"b1ad38af4aaa50435c1111553fe9bd3eba8c9182b520070da1cdbe9103c57a05"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me get started. I'll work on multiple things in parallel — implementing features into myself while setting up to run the EXP experiments.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_espcdpkyk6ce_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/dev/temporal-attention/event_store.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":523,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":53959,"totalTokens":54525,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774115192068}}
{"type":"message","id":"dc0e70a6","parentId":"37ba686f","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:46:55.162Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_espcdpkyk6ce_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"\nEventBasedStore: Decay based on events, not wall-clock time.\n\nInstead of time ticking away, decay is a product of:\n1. Message count (new interactions)\n2. Focus shift (topic changed)\n\nThis fits conversation/memory better than time-based decay.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom datetime import datetime\nfrom typing import Any, Optional\nimport math\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass Fact:\n    key: str\n    value: Any\n    valid_from_message: int = 0  # Message count when fact was added\n    valid_to_message: Optional[int] = None  # When fact became invalid\n    focus_id: str = \"default\"  # Topic/focus group\n    access_count: int = 0\n    last_accessed_message: int = 0\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass ScoredFact:\n    fact: Fact\n    message_decay: float  # Based on message count\n    focus_decay: float  # Based on focus shift\n    attention_score: float  # Based on access patterns\n    combined_score: float\n\n\nclass EventBasedStore:\n    \"\"\"\n    Decay based on events, not time.\n    \n    Key idea: In conversation, what matters isn't wall-clock time -\n    it's how many messages have passed and whether the topic shifted.\n    \n    Decay formula:\n    - message_decay: e^(-0.693 * messages_since_added / half_life_messages)\n    - focus_decay: 1.0 if same focus, 0.5 if shifted\n    - total_decay = message_decay * focus_decay\n    \n    Attention still applies within decay.\n    \"\"\"\n    \n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        message_half_life: int = 50,  # Messages until decay to 0.5\n        focus_decay_factor: float = 0.5,  # Multiplier when focus shifts\n        temporal_weight: float = 0.9,\n        attention_weight: float = 0.1,\n        initial_focus: str = \"default\",\n    ):\n        self.facts: dict[str, list[Fact]] = {}\n        self.message_count = 0\n        self.current_focus = initial_focus  # Start with a focus\n        \n        self.message_half_life = message_half_life\n        self.focus_decay_factor = focus_decay_factor\n        self.temporal_weight = temporal_weight\n        self.attention_weight = attention_weight\n    \n    def advance(self, focus: Optional[str] = None):\n        \"\"\"Advance the message count. Call after each message.\"\"\"\n        self.message_count += 1\n        if focus:\n            if focus != self.current_focus:\n                # Focus shifted - apply decay\n                self._apply_focus_decay(focus)\n                self.current_focus = focus\n    \n    def _apply_focus_decay(self, new_focus: str):\n        \"\"\"When focus shifts, decay facts that are NOT in the new focus.\"\"\"\n        old_focus = self.current_focus\n        for facts in self.facts.values():\n            for fact in facts:\n                # Only decay facts that are NOT in the new focus\n                if fact.focus_id != new_focus and \"_decayed\" not in fact.focus_id:\n                    # Mark as decayed - will get focus_decay_factor\n                    fact.focus_id = f\"{fact.focus_id}_was_{old_focus}\"\n    \n    def put(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        value: Any,\n        valid_from_message: Optional[int] = None,\n        valid_to_message: Optional[int] = None,\n        focus: Optional[str] = None,\n    ):\n        \"\"\"Add a fact at current message count.\"\"\"\n        if valid_from_message is None:\n            valid_from_message = self.message_count\n        \n        fact = Fact(\n            key=key,\n            value=value,\n            valid_from_message=valid_from_message,\n            valid_to_message=valid_to_message,\n            focus_id=focus or self.current_focus,\n        )\n        \n        if key not in self.facts:\n            self.facts[key] = []\n        self.facts[key].append(fact)\n    \n    def get(self, key: str, at_message: Optional[int] = None) -> Optional[ScoredFact]:\n        \"\"\"Get best fact at given message count.\"\"\"\n        if at_message is None:\n            at_message = self.message_count\n        \n        if key not in self.facts:\n            return None\n        \n        facts = self.facts[key]\n        valid_facts = []\n        \n        for fact in facts:\n            # Check validity\n            if fact.valid_from_message > at_message:\n                continue  # Not yet valid\n            if fact.valid_to_message is not None and fact.valid_to_message <= at_message:\n                continue  # No longer valid\n            \n            # Calculate scores\n            msg_decay = self._message_decay(fact, at_message)\n            focus_decay = self._focus_decay(fact)\n            attention = self._attention(fact, at_message)\n            \n            temporal_score = msg_decay * focus_decay\n            \n            # FIXED: Small recency bonus to prefer newer facts when tied\n            recency_bonus = 0.0001 * (self.message_count - fact.valid_from_message)\n            \n            # FIXED: Attention has NEGLIGIBLE effect (just breaks true ties)\n            combined = temporal_score * (1 + 0.001 * attention) + recency_bonus\n            \n            valid_facts.append(ScoredFact(\n                fact=fact,\n                message_decay=msg_decay,\n                focus_decay=focus_decay,\n                attention_score=attention,\n                combined_score=combined,\n            ))\n        \n        if not valid_facts:\n            return None\n        \n        valid_facts.sort(key=lambda x: x.combined_score, reverse=True)\n        return valid_facts[0]\n    \n    def _message_decay(self, fact: Fact, at_message: int) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Decay based on message count, not wall-clock time.\"\"\"\n        messages_since = at_message - fact.valid_from_message\n        if messages_since < 0:\n            messages_since = 0\n        decay = math.exp(-0.693 * messages_since / self.message_half_life)\n        return min(1.0, max(0.0, decay))\n    \n    def _focus_decay(self, fact: Fact) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Decay based on focus shift.\"\"\"\n        if fact.focus_id == self.current_focus:\n            return 1.0\n        elif \"_decayed\" in fact.focus_id:\n            return self.focus_decay_factor\n        else:\n            # Same focus_id but not current - partially decayed\n            return self.focus_decay_factor\n    \n    def _attention(self, fact: Fact, at_message: int) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Score based on access count - NEGLIGIBLE effect.\"\"\"\n        if fact.access_count == 0:\n            return 0.0\n        # Large denominator - attention should almost never overcome temporal\n        count_score = math.log1p(fact.access_count) / 100  # Max ~0.07 for 1000 accesses\n        \n        # Recency of access matters too\n        messages_since_access = at_message - fact.last_accessed_message\n        if messages_since_access < 0:\n            messages_since_access = 0\n        access_decay = math.exp(-0.693 * messages_since_access / (self.message_half_life / 2))\n        \n        return min(1.0, count_score * access_decay)\n    \n    def access(self, key: str):\n        \"\"\"Record access at current message count.\"\"\"\n        if key in self.facts:\n            latest = max(self.facts[key], key=lambda f: f.valid_from_message)\n            latest.access_count += 1\n            latest.last_accessed_message = self.message_count\n    \n    def get_all(self, key: str, at_message: Optional[int] = None) -> list[ScoredFact]:\n        \"\"\"Get all valid facts for a key.\"\"\"\n        if at_message is None:\n            at_message = self.message_count\n        \n        if key not in self.facts:\n            return []\n        \n        facts = self.facts[key]\n        results = []\n        \n        for fact in facts:\n            if fact.valid_from_message > at_message:\n                continue\n            if fact.valid_to_message is not None and fact.valid_to_message <= at_message:\n                continue\n            \n            msg_decay = self._message_decay(fact, at_message)\n            focus_decay = self._focus_decay(fact)\n            attention = self._attention(fact, at_message)\n            \n            temporal = msg_decay * focus_decay\n            combined = temporal * (1 + self.attention_weight * attention)\n            \n            results.append(ScoredFact(\n                fact=fact,\n                message_decay=msg_decay,\n                focus_decay=focus_decay,\n                attention_score=attention,\n                combined_score=combined,\n            ))\n        \n        results.sort(key=lambda x: x.combined_score, reverse=True)\n        return results\n    \n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f\"EventBasedStore(msgs={self.message_count}, focus={self.current_focus}, keys={len(self.facts)})\"\n\n\n# Demo\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    store = EventBasedStore(\n        message_half_life=50,\n        focus_decay_factor=0.5,\n        temporal_weight=0.9,\n        attention_weight=0.1,\n    )\n    \n    print(\"=\"*60)\n    print(\"EVENT-BASED DECAY DEMO\")\n    print(\"=\"*60)\n    \n    # Message 1: Set up initial fact\n    store.put(\"topic\", \"attention\")\n    print(f\"\\n[Msg {store.message_count}] Added: topic=attention\")\n    \n    # Message 2-5: Advance, access the fact\n    for _ in range(4):\n        store.advance()\n    store.access(\"topic\")\n    store.access(\"topic\")\n    print(f\"[Msg {store.message_count}] Accessed topic 2x\")\n    \n    # Message 6: Ask about it\n    result = store.get(\"topic\")\n    print(f\"[Msg {store.message_count}] Query topic: {result.fact.value}\")\n    print(f\"  Scores: msg_decay={result.message_decay:.2f}, focus={result.focus_decay:.2f}, attention={result.attention_score:.2f}\")\n    \n    # Message 7-20: Lots of messages but same topic\n    for _ in range(14):\n        store.advance()\n    print(f\"\\n[Msg {store.message_count}] Advanced 14 messages (same topic)\")\n    \n    result = store.get(\"topic\")\n    print(f\"Query topic: {result.fact.value}\")\n    print(f\"  Scores: msg_decay={result.message_decay:.2f}\")\n    # Note: message_decay drops!\n    \n    # Message 21: Topic shifts!\n    store.advance(focus=\"weather\")\n    print(f\"\\n[Msg {store.message_count}] FOCUS SHIFTED to: weather\")\n    \n    # Add new fact under new focus\n    store.put(\"topic\", \"weather_info\")\n    result = store.get(\"topic\")\n    print(f\"Query topic: {result.fact.value}\")\n    print(f\"  Scores: msg_decay={result.message_decay:.2f}, focus={result.focus_decay:.2f}\")\n    # The attention fact should be heavily decayed!\n    \n    print(\"\\n\" + \"=\"*60)\n    print(\"KEY INSIGHT:\")\n    print(\"- Decay based on MESSAGE COUNT, not wall-clock time\")\n    print(\"- Focus shift applies extra decay\")\n    print(\"- Conversation naturally 'forgets' as it advances\")\n    print(\"=\"*60)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774115215157}}
{"type":"message","id":"901561a6","parentId":"dc0e70a6","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:47:47.650Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the temporal attention event store. Let me think about how to adapt this for my own memory system.\n\nFor my file-based memory system, I can't run this in-memory since I don't have a persistent Python process. But I can:\n1. Create a wrapper that simulates focus decay in my memory files\n2. Add decay metadata to my memory entries\n3. Periodically \"clean\" old entries based on conversation turns\n\nLet me think about what I can implement:\n\n1. **Focus decay for memory** — I'll create a `memory_decay` module that wraps my memory system with focus decay. When I record a memory, I'll include focus/topic metadata. When I retrieve, I'll apply decay based on conversation turns and focus shifts.\n\n\n2. **Provenance metadata** — I can start tagging my responses with structured metadata that tracks confidence and source information.\n3. **Self-improvement** — I'll set up a cron job that periodically reviews my code, generates improvements, and validates them before applying.\n4. **Experiments** — I need to run the EXP experiments. Since I don't have the Python environment set up, I'll need to check what's available first, then execute the appropriate scripts.\n\nLet me start implementing these features. First, I'll build the memory decay wrapper, then tackle the cron job for self-improvement.\n\nActually, I should be strategic about this. I'll create a memory decay module that adapts the event_store concept for file-based memory, set up the cron job to trigger self-improvement, and run the EXP experiments in parallel.","thinkingSignature":"9f55e6419e8452c3d0913437f429ae97475fd81465f0f6486696f08f42107dc2"},{"type":"text","text":"Good — I have what I need. Let me implement everything in parallel. I'll build the focus decay memory system, set up the self-improvement cron, and kick off the experiments all at once.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vnd2ytb62toc_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\event_store.py","content":"\"\"\"\nFocusDecayMemory: File-based memory with focus decay.\n\nAdapted from temporal-attention/event_store.py by toxzak-svg.\nThe core idea: in conversation, what matters isn't wall-clock time —\nit's how many messages have passed and whether the topic shifted.\n\nDecay formula:\n  message_decay  = e^(-0.693 * messages_since / half_life)\n  focus_decay    = 1.0 if same focus, 0.5 if shifted\n  combined       = message_decay * focus_decay\n\nEach entry in MEMORY.md or daily notes can carry focus metadata.\nWhen the topic shifts, facts from the old topic decay.\n\nUsage (in agent code):\n  from memory.event_store import FocusDecayMemory\n  store = FocusDecayMemory.load()\n  store.put(\"user_name\", \"Zach\", focus=\"personal\")\n  store.advance(focus=\"work\")\n  store.put(\"project\", \"Component Crate\", focus=\"work\")\n  result = store.get(\"user_name\")  # decayed if focus shifted\n  store.save()\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import Any, Optional\nimport math\nimport json\nimport re\nimport os\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nMEMORY_FILE = Path(__file__).parent / \"focus_decay_memory.json\"\nMESSAGE_COUNT_FILE = Path(__file__).parent / \"message_count.json\"\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass MemoryFact:\n    key: str\n    value: Any\n    valid_from_message: int = 0\n    valid_to_message: Optional[int] = None\n    focus_id: str = \"default\"\n    access_count: int = 0\n    last_accessed_message: int = 0\n    provenance: str = \"unknown\"  # where did this come from?\n    confidence: float = 1.0  # 0-1, how confident are we?\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass ScoredFact:\n    fact: MemoryFact\n    message_decay: float\n    focus_decay: float\n    attention_score: float\n    combined_score: float\n\n\nclass FocusDecayMemory:\n    \"\"\"\n    Event-based decay memory for file-based storage.\n\n    Call advance() after every user message.\n    Call put(key, value, focus=\"...\") to record a fact.\n    Call get(key) to retrieve — applies decay automatically.\n    Call save() to persist to disk.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        message_half_life: int = 30,\n        focus_decay_factor: float = 0.5,\n        attention_weight: float = 0.05,\n    ):\n        self.facts: dict[str, list[MemoryFact]] = {}\n        self.message_count = 0\n        self.current_focus = \"default\"\n        self.half_life = message_half_life\n        self.focus_decay_factor = focus_decay_factor\n        self.attention_weight = attention_weight\n\n    # ─── Persistence ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n    @classmethod\n    def load(cls) -> \"FocusDecayMemory\":\n        if MEMORY_FILE.exists():\n            try:\n                data = json.loads(MEMORY_FILE.read_text())\n                store = cls(\n                    message_half_life=data.get(\"half_life\", 30),\n                    focus_decay_factor=data.get(\"focus_decay_factor\", 0.5),\n                    attention_weight=data.get(\"attention_weight\", 0.05),\n                )\n                store.message_count = data.get(\"message_count\", 0)\n                store.current_focus = data.get(\"current_focus\", \"default\")\n                for key, entries in data.get(\"facts\", {}).items():\n                    store.facts[key] = [MemoryFact(**e) for e in entries]\n                return store\n            except Exception:\n                pass\n        return cls()\n\n    def save(self):\n        data = {\n            \"half_life\": self.half_life,\n            \"focus_decay_factor\": self.focus_decay_factor,\n            \"attention_weight\": self.attention_weight,\n            \"message_count\": self.message_count,\n            \"current_focus\": self.current_focus,\n            \"facts\": {k: [f.__dict__ for f in entries] for k, entries in self.facts.items()},\n        }\n        MEMORY_FILE.write_text(json.dumps(data, indent=2, default=str))\n\n    # ─── Core API ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n    def advance(self, focus: Optional[str] = None):\n        \"\"\"Call after each user message. Advances message count + optionally shifts focus.\"\"\"\n        self.message_count += 1\n        if focus and focus != self.current_focus:\n            self._apply_focus_decay(focus)\n            self.current_focus = focus\n\n    def put(\n        self,\n        key: str,\n        value: Any,\n        focus: Optional[str] = None,\n        provenance: str = \"unknown\",\n        confidence: float = 1.0,\n        valid_from_message: Optional[int] = None,\n    ):\n        \"\"\"Store a fact under a key.\"\"\"\n        if valid_from_message is None:\n            valid_from_message = self.message_count\n\n        fact = MemoryFact(\n            key=key,\n            value=value,\n            valid_from_message=valid_from_message,\n            focus_id=focus or self.current_focus,\n            provenance=provenance,\n            confidence=confidence,\n        )\n        if key not in self.facts:\n            self.facts[key] = []\n        self.facts[key].append(fact)\n\n    def get(self, key: str, at_message: Optional[int] = None) -> Optional[ScoredFact]:\n        \"\"\"Get the best (highest-scoring) fact for a key, with decay applied.\"\"\"\n        if at_message is None:\n            at_message = self.message_count\n        if key not in self.facts:\n            return None\n\n        valid = []\n        for fact in self.facts[key]:\n            if fact.valid_from_message > at_message:\n                continue\n            if fact.valid_to_message is not None and fact.valid_to_message <= at_message:\n                continue\n\n            msg_decay = self._message_decay(fact, at_message)\n            focus_decay = self._focus_decay(fact)\n            attention = self._attention(fact, at_message)\n\n            temporal = msg_decay * focus_decay\n            recency_bonus = 0.0001 * (self.message_count - fact.valid_from_message)\n            combined = temporal * (1 + self.attention_weight * attention) + recency_bonus\n            combined *= fact.confidence  # Factor in confidence\n\n            valid.append(ScoredFact(fact, msg_decay, focus_decay, attention, combined))\n\n        if not valid:\n            return None\n        valid.sort(key=lambda x: x.combined_score, reverse=True)\n        best = valid[0]\n        self.access(key)  # record the access\n        return best\n\n    def get_all(self, key: str, at_message: Optional[int] = None) -> list[ScoredFact]:\n        \"\"\"Get all valid scored facts for a key.\"\"\"\n        if at_message is None:\n            at_message = self.message_count\n        if key not in self.facts:\n            return []\n\n        results = []\n        for fact in self.facts[key]:\n            if fact.valid_from_message > at_message:\n                continue\n            if fact.valid_to_message is not None and fact.valid_to_message <= at_message:\n                continue\n            msg_decay = self._message_decay(fact, at_message)\n            focus_decay = self._focus_decay(fact)\n            attention = self._attention(fact, at_message)\n            temporal = msg_decay * focus_decay\n            combined = temporal * (1 + self.attention_weight * attention) * fact.confidence\n            results.append(ScoredFact(fact, msg_decay, focus_decay, attention, combined))\n\n        results.sort(key=lambda x: x.combined_score, reverse=True)\n        return results\n\n    def access(self, key: str):\n        \"\"\"Record an access at current message count.\"\"\"\n        if key in self.facts:\n            latest = max(self.facts[key], key=lambda f: f.valid_from_message)\n            latest.access_count += 1\n            latest.last_accessed_message = self.message_count\n\n    def search(self, query: str, threshold: float = 0.1) -> list[tuple[str, float]]:\n        \"\"\"\n        Simple substring search across fact values.\n        Returns [(key, combined_score), ...] for facts whose value matches query.\n        \"\"\"\n        results = []\n        query_lower = query.lower()\n        for key, entries in self.facts.items():\n            for fact in entries:\n                if fact.valid_from_message > self.message_count:\n                    continue\n                if fact.valid_to_message is not None and fact.valid_to_message <= self.message_count:\n                    continue\n                val_str = str(fact.value).lower()\n                if query_lower in val_str:\n                    msg_decay = self._message_decay(fact, self.message_count)\n                    focus_decay = self._focus_decay(fact)\n                    combined = msg_decay * focus_decay * fact.confidence\n                    if combined >= threshold:\n                        results.append((key, combined))\n        results.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n        return results\n\n    def gc(self):\n        \"\"\"Garbage collect: remove facts with combined_score near zero.\"\"\"\n        survivors = {}\n        for key, entries in self.facts.items():\n            kept = []\n            for fact in entries:\n                score = self._message_decay(fact, self.message_count) * self._focus_decay(fact) * fact.confidence\n                if score > 0.001:\n                    kept.append(fact)\n            if kept:\n                survivors[key] = kept\n        self.facts = survivors\n\n    # ─── Internal decay calculations ─────────────────────────────\n\n    def _message_decay(self, fact: MemoryFact, at_message: int) -> float:\n        messages_since = max(0, at_message - fact.valid_from_message)\n        decay = math.exp(-0.693 * messages_since / max(1, self.half_life))\n        return min(1.0, max(0.0, decay))\n\n    def _focus_decay(self, fact: MemoryFact) -> float:\n        if fact.focus_id == self.current_focus:\n            return 1.0\n        if \"_decayed\" in fact.focus_id:\n            return self.focus_decay_factor\n        return self.focus_decay_factor\n\n    def _attention(self, fact: MemoryFact, at_message: int) -> float:\n        if fact.access_count == 0:\n            return 0.0\n        count_score = math.log1p(fact.access_count) / 100\n        messages_since = max(0, at_message - fact.last_accessed_message)\n        access_decay = math.exp(-0.693 * messages_since / max(1, self.half_life // 2))\n        return min(1.0, count_score * access_decay)\n\n    def _apply_focus_decay(self, new_focus: str):\n        old_focus = self.current_focus\n        for facts in self.facts.values():\n            for fact in facts:\n                if fact.focus_id != new_focus and \"_decayed\" not in fact.focus_id:\n                    fact.focus_id = f\"{fact.focus_id}_was_{old_focus}\"\n\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f\"FocusDecayMemory(msgs={self.message_count}, focus={self.current_focus}, keys={len(self.facts)})\"\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":45067,"output":2772,"cacheRead":11874,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59713,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774115215166}}
