{"type":"message","id":"dbaeb89b","parentId":"f675d323","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:50:04.052Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I'm also looking at the issue - the function check_memory_health has `\"memory return {` which was a typo. The return statement was split across lines in a weird way. Now it should be fixed. Let me also check that the check_memory_health function is correct.\n\nActually wait, looking at the original code I wrote, the return statement was:\n```\n    return {\n_\"files\": len(recent_files),```\n\nBut actually the original was correct, the issue was that the markdown rendering I saw was confusing. The issue was that `\"memory return {` was the output, which means the original code probably had:\n```python\nreturn {  # \"memory return {\" was a split across lines error in my original file generation\n\n\n```\n\nActually no - I just wrote the file and the \"memory return {\" string appeared. Let me re-read my original write command. Oh I see - the issue is that when I wrote the file with `write`, something went wrong in the multi-line string. The `return {` was on one line and `_files` was supposed to be a continuation but got mangled. The function was trying to return a dictionary but the key had a leading underscore and the word \"memory\" was part of some error message. The `\"memory return {` pattern suggests I accidentally concatenated the string literal with the return statement somehow.\n\nLooking at the raw bytes in the file, it seems like when the f-string was split across lines in my original template, the continuation got corrupted - the `return {` ended up on a separate line and the f-string prefix got lost, so the Python interpreter saw it as invalid syntax instead of a proper dictionary return statement.\n\n```\n    \"memory return {\n_files\": len(recent_files),\n```\n\nThis got interpreted as a string literal followed by a return statement with a syntax error. The fix was straightforwa